# Project Rules

## General Principles

* Write production-quality code.
* Prioritize readability over cleverness.
* Follow SOLID principles where appropriate.
* Keep files focused and maintainable.
* Avoid premature optimization.
* Every commit should improve the codebase.

---

## Architecture

* Use the Next.js App Router.
* Use TypeScript
* Organize code by feature rather than file type.
* Prefer composition over inheritance.
* Keep business logic separate from UI.

---

## Folder Structure

Use this structure whenever possible:

app/
components/
components/ui/
components/shared/
components/features/
lib/
hooks/
services/
types/
utils/
constants/
public/

Do not create deeply nested folders unless necessary.

---

## Naming Conventions

Components:
PascalCase

Example:
BrokerCard.tsx

Hooks:
useSomething.ts

Utilities:
camelCase

Types:
PascalCase

Constants:
UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

---

## Imports

Order imports as:

1. React / Next.js
2. Third-party libraries
3. Internal components
4. Hooks
5. Utilities
6. Types
7. Styles

Remove unused imports.

---

## Code Quality

Avoid:

* duplicated logic
* magic numbers
* dead code
* console.log
* commented-out code

Prefer extracting reusable utilities.

---

## Data

If the same JSX appears more than twice,
extract it into a reusable component.

If multiple cards differ only by content,
store their content in arrays and render using map().

---

## Error Handling

Every data-driven component should consider:

* loading state
* empty state
* error state

Never assume data exists.

---

## Performance

* Minimize client-side JavaScript.
* Prefer Server Components.
* Lazy-load heavy components.
* Optimize images.
* Avoid unnecessary rerenders.

---

## Before Completing Any Task

Always review:

* readability
* responsiveness
* accessibility
* duplication
* performance
* maintainability
* semantic HTML

Never consider a task complete without reviewing your own code.
